{"cursor":"18782","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox aircraft program |name = Amerika Bomber (aviation design competition)\n|image = File:Bundesarchiv Bild 146-1995-042-37, Schwerer Bomber Messerschmitt\nMe 264 V1.jpg |caption = The Messerschmitt Me 264 V1 (first prototype Me 264)\n|aim = |requirement = |issuer = Reich Air Ministry |service = Luftwaffe |value =\n|initiated = April 1942 |expected = |proposals = Focke-Wulf, Heinkel, Junkers,\nand Messerschmitt (conventional bombers) |prototypes = Focke-Wulf Fw 300 Focke-\nWulf Ta 400  Heinkel He 277  Junkers Ju 390 Messerschmitt Me 264.\n|concluded = July 1944, with the ''JÃ¤gernotprogramm''. |outcome = Five\nprototypes (two Ju 390, three Me 264) built, no operational aircraft\n|predecessors = Ural bomber  Heinkel He 177 |successors = |related = }}\n\nThe 'Amerika-Bomber' project was an initiative of the German [[Ministry of\nAviation (Germany)|Reichsluftfahrtministerium]], to obtain a long-range\nstrategic bomber for the [[Luftwaffe]] that would be capable of striking the\ncontinental United States from Germany, a distance of about . Though the concept\nwas raised as early as 1938, plans for such advanced, long range strategic\nbomber designs did not begin to appear in Reichsmarschall Hermann GÃ¶ring's\noffices until 1942. Various proposals were put forward, including using it to\ndeliver an atomic bomb, but they were all eventually abandoned as too expensive,\nand potentially consuming far too much of Germany's steadily shrinking aviation\nproduction capacity after 1942.\n","linknr":331,"url":"Amerika_Bomber","recorded":1375087484,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Amerika_Bomber&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Amerika_Bomber&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debu